snippet.textDisplay:
As an extrovert, I can relate. I showed it to my husband, an introvert, who doesn’t really get stir crazy.

At 0:36, when you sang about the neighbors, my husband laughed and said “that’s you!”. I literally check on my garden of six plants three times a day in the hopes a neighbor will be within shouting distance. (Staring at my flat of seedlings has yet to produce results...) I am thankful we have a yard so I can get out without leaving the property!

I am also thankful for Zoom, TwoSeven, and Discord, so I can get together with friends virtually—do some watch parties or play Guild Wars 2. I have a feeling that going to be the only thing that keeps me sane. Because I love to read, but it can only take me so far without social interaction!

snippet.textDisplay:
Bored? Whats that? Heck I did a three week stint in December (my holiday time), by myself. Only sticking my nose out to get food about once a week. I loved it :-) My usual yearly routine.


There are so many things one can do, even without the internet. But with it the world is at your finger tips.


You can take naps, read books, do puzzles. Paint (the house or on paper), build/make things. Learn a new skill (my latest interests have been blender and Linux). There were days when people used to have hobbies. Think it is good time for people to start doing that again. Use something like Secondlife to have a social life and get to know people from all around the world.


If you have a skill to help those trying to help us, like sewing, 3D printing and so on, find how you can help. There is no excuse to have nothing to do.
